                <item>
            <title>Focused Reading</title>
            <link>https://carlbarenbrug.com/@/page/I1kxTiZh4wiccGAz</link>
            <guid isPermaLink="false">blog/focused-reading</guid>
            <pubDate>Sat, 07 Dec 2020 00:00:00 +0100</pubDate>
            <description><![CDATA[<p>I have never been a particularly big reader. I enjoy books and I enjoy reading blog posts, but I seem to make more room for the latter, even though I enjoy reading novels far more than I do blogs. The reason is simple enough: I spend the vast majority of my day behind a computer screen for work, side projects, writing, editing, and entertainment. And when I am away from the screen I focus on my physical health, or spending time with people, or resting. OK, enough of the excuses. What I want to talk about is the beauty of focused reading. Or better yet, completely undistracted reading.</p>
<p>How we read is highly variable, whether it is print books, ebooks, blogs, newspapers, magazines, emails, newsletters, news articles, forums, or social media posts. And how distracting each of these forms can also vary massively. It is often a far from focused reading experience, let alone a pleasurable one. How do you read without distractions? Most of these reading forms pulls us away from the others with alerts and updates coming in frequently, vying for our attention.</p>
<p>One of the main reasons I enjoy reading books more than I do most of the aforementioned forms, is because 99% of books are entirely focused on the written word. There is also no danger of receiving notifications if you’re reading a print book or Kindle ebook. Leave your tech behind, find a comfortable spot, and enjoy a read in silence. It can be a fully immersive experience and that is what a lot of authors aim to achieve.</p>
<p>When it comes to reading blogs, I am always happy when I find ones that are focused entirely on the reading experience. No sidebars, no ads, no pop-ups, no need to install additional browser extensions. With that said, I think it is a good idea to install apps like <a href="https://nextdns.io" rel="noreferrer" target="_blank">NextDNS</a> and <a href="https://1blocker.com" rel="noreferrer" target="_blank">1Blocker</a>—it results in a much quicker and cleaner browsing experience overall. A few fine examples of sites that focus on your reading experience are:</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="https://ia.net/design/blog" rel="noreferrer" target="_blank">ia.net/design/blog</a></li>
<li><a href="https://manuelmoreale.com" rel="noreferrer" target="_blank">manuelmoreale.com</a></li>
<li><a href="https://electricgecko.de" rel="noreferrer" target="_blank">electricgecko.de</a></li>
<li><a href="https://mnmlist.com" rel="noreferrer" target="_blank">mnmlist.com</a></li>
<li><a href="https://minimalissimo.com" rel="noreferrer" target="_blank">minimalissimo.com</a></li>
</ul>
<p>Visually noisy sites are largely the reason RSS readers are still widely used, which strip away the design and leave the absolute essentials, sometimes offering a better aesthetic too. But even browsers such as Safari have inbuilt Reader options that work in a similar fashion.</p>
<p>I think the same focused reading approach can be taken with newsletters depending on the topic. If a newsletter is delivered in plain text, even better. Keep it as light as you can if you are sending them. How you receive mail will largely depend on your mail client, but unfortunately there is not a huge amount you can do to control the consistency of how you read emails.</p>
<p>As for reading social media, whether it be Twitter, Facebook, or Instagram, opening these sites for short periods at scheduled times of the day means you avoid getting lost in the noise and distracting you from more important or enjoyable reading. A quick scan and light engagement will usually suffice. It is how I have been using social media for the past six months and it is a much better reading experience for me. Or you can just forget social media entirely.</p>]]></description>
            <author>cmhbarenbrug@gmail.com (Carl Barenbrug)</author>
        </item>
                <item>
            <title>Building a Membership</title>
            <link>https://carlbarenbrug.com/@/page/7yKQgNyHNlkpOkBR</link>
            <guid isPermaLink="false">blog/building-a-membership</guid>
            <pubDate>Sat, 07 Dec 2020 00:00:00 +0100</pubDate>
            <description><![CDATA[<p>In late spring of 2020, <a href="https://minimalissimo.com" rel="noreferrer" target="_blank">Minimalissimo</a> introduced a <a href="https://minimalissimo.com/membership" rel="noreferrer" target="_blank">membership</a> platform as a means to generate passive income for greater sustainability, engage more with our community, design things members can use, discover how advertisement-free reading is valued, and determine to what extent creators we feature value our magazine as a promotional tool for their work.</p>
<p>From Day 1 of this membership, I viewed it as an experiment with low expectation. Given the simplicity of the membership signup process (a brainchild of <a href="https://manuelmoreale.com" rel="noreferrer" target="_blank">Manu</a>) and how effortlessly and unobtrusively we introduced the concept throughout the website, I thought it would appeal to a small proportion of readers, ignored by some, and overlooked by others. Gradually however, the membership has grown, but it is at a snail’s pace and the numbers are modest. Sure, some people simply signup for the perks and then cease their support once they have what they want (I have no time for those people), and others support us without even a consideration of the perks (I love those people). Then we have members who support us and also enjoy all the perks we offer (I also love those people).</p>
<p>Site visits to <a href="https://minimalissimo.com" rel="noreferrer" target="_blank">minimalissimo.com</a> fluctuate throughout the year but we still hit +50k per month, so this can give me a rough idea of how many readers (as well as social media followers) might become members. To be honest though, I couldn't care less about web analytics. They are becoming increasingly unreliable through the introduction of private browsers and extensions (fuck cookies). Same goes for social media followers, where people barely see any of the content we publish due to those wonderful algorithms we all love to complain about.</p>
<p>With modest membership numbers, but positive reactions, I am going to persevere with this model for the foreseeable future. I have also set a tentative goal to reach 100 core members. That will cover almost all of our overheads to keep the site running smoothly and consistently. Whether we reach that in two months or twelve, I don’t really mind, because we will continue to experiment with this platform and how else to introduce it to our community of readers.</p>
<p>I live with the hope and intention that eventually donations from our members will form the core income stream for Minimalissimo, and our <a href="https://minimalissimo.shop" rel="noreferrer" target="_blank">online shop</a> will be supplementary to that. That will obviously need to far exceed 100 members, but I don’t think it is an insurmountable challenge.</p>
<p>You can read more about the <a href="https://minimalissimo.com/articles/minimalissimo-membership" rel="noreferrer" target="_blank">rationale</a> behind the Minimalissimo membership and if you are interested in <a href="https://minimalissimo.com/membership" rel="noreferrer" target="_blank">becoming a member</a> yourself, then I would greatly appreciate and welcome your support.</p>
<p>And if you are curious about what the perks are, you get:</p>
<ul>
<li>Digital magazine bundle</li>
<li>Wallpapers library</li>
<li>Members email list to discuss plans, ideas, and experiments</li>
<li>Select product discounts</li>
</ul>]]></description>
            <author>cmhbarenbrug@gmail.com (Carl Barenbrug)</author>
